Every picture tells a story don’t it? This first photo is from June 2018. It was the first official work session/table read for “Almost Famous”. There were only a handful of us in the room and only 2 of us would remain throughout the whole entire process for one reason or another (sup @_solaylay ). I was overjoyed to be in a room with Tom Kitt again and to be working with the legendary Cameron Crowe. 

We read through scenes from the show in no particular order. I accompanied Tom Kitt on Guitar as he played piano and sang “The Nighttime sky’s got nothing on you” for us for the very first time. I played 100 roles. We read through scenes and tried to make sense of the world all together. A truly collaborative effort from creatives to cast. That continued for 5 years.

I watched and participated as the show literally took flight from that table read to where we are now. These people really did become my family and I wouldn’t change a goddamn thing (see 2nd photo in slide taken by the incomparable @jennyandersonphoto )

I wish we could’ve kept this beautiful show alive for a little longer. I wish the world could know the blood sweat and tears that went into making this show. It has proudly been an enormous part of my professional makeup for the last 5 years and today I must say farewell.

So, as my guy Dick Roswell so eloquently states: 

I’m not good at goodbyes. Goodbye. ❤️
This is coming up soon and I could not be more excited. Come hear some original tunes by yours truly and these fantastic artists!

We’re Baaaaaack 🎄 🔔 🎁 ❄️. 
13th Annual Merry Merry! 

A blurb from Joe: 

A New York City Twisted Holiday Tradition celebrates its Thirteenth Year of putting the “extra” in “extravaganza!”

They say that good things come to those who wait, and Mr. Iconis is pleased to announce that after three bah humbug years of pandemic pause, Christmas is coming like never before. Joe and his merry band of musical theater punks are proud to reignite their legendary holiday tradition and bring their insane celebration of all things red and green back to 54 Below.

Written by Joe Iconis, directed by John Simpkins, and produced by Jennifer Ashley Tepper, this wild yuletide explosion is part rock concert, part theater piece, and part theme park attraction come to life. Featuring brand new holiday songs, old favorites, a huge cast of musical theater all-stars, tiny elves, enormous reindeer, an inebriated Mr. and Mrs. Claus, and more whiskey-fueled shenanigans than you can shake a candy cane at, it promises to be the hap-hap-happiest holiday hoedown ever seen on stage.

Yule Logs,
Joseph Christmas Iconis

Just happened upon this photo from the early 2010s and simply needed to repost it because it STILL encapsulates me at all times. Just carrying a bunch of gear through New York on the way to / coming from a gig. Bemused but satisfied. Exhausted but driven. Usually dressed in black ( I allow more color these days). Sure some things have changed; I have a beautiful and wonderfully supportive and equally driven wife + two amazing doggos and a house in Brooklyn. In part, I got here because of what I have always done. I’m still out here doing this damn thing and I wouldn’t trade it for the world. Come see me play with @erl_emorequestlive at @thesultanroom on 1/6 as I kick off yet another endeavor to keep living my dreams.
